## Migration: Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Why this breaks

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. The entire pattern — `ThreadAbortException`, `ResetAbort`, forced thread termination — is gone. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation**.

### Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Cleanup on cancellation | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` in Stop | Blocking wait for shutdown | `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne` / `Join(timeout)` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock waits
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic as the old ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we simply continue to loop exit
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive, there's no force-kill equivalent.
        // The thread will exit at its next cancellation checkpoint.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Changes to `GetNextItem`

If `GetNextItem` blocks (e.g., on a queue), it **must** accept and respect the token:

```csharp
// Before: blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could unwedge it
private WorkItem GetNextItem() => _queue.Take();

// After: throws OperationCanceledException when token fires
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) => _queue.Take(token);
```

For `BlockingCollection<T>.Take(token)`, `SemaphoreSlim.Wait(token)`, etc., cancellation support is built in.

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Impact |
|---------|--------|
| **Not passing token to blocking calls** | Thread hangs forever — cancellation only works at checkpoints |
| **Using `Thread.Sleep` instead of `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne`** | Sleep ignores the token; thread won't wake until sleep expires |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and registered callbacks |
| **Expecting immediate stop** | Cooperative cancellation only fires at the next check — design accordingly |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to avoid swallowing unrelated exceptions |

### If `GetNextItem` calls code you can't modify

Move uncooperative work to a child process and use `Process.Kill()` as a last resort — it's the only true force-termination available in modern .NET.
